  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for a camel to go through a needles eye",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] To soften the apparent harshness of this expression, some have conjectured ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kamilon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘a rope;’ and some have explained ‘the needle’s eye’ of the small side gate for passengers (at the side of the large city gates), through which a camel might press its way, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "if it were first unladen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " But (i) the conjecture ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Kamilon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is wholly without authority, (ii) The name of ‘the needle’s eye’ applied to small gates is probably a modern one which has actually originated from an attempt to soften this verse:—at any rate there is no ancient trace of it. (iii) The Rabbinic parallels are decisive to prove that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a camel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is meant because the Babylonian Jews using the same proverb substitute ‘an elephant’ for ‘a camel.’ (iv) It is the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "object",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the proverb to express ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "human i?npossibility.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "human ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "sphere—apart from the special grace of God—it would be certain that those who ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " riches would be led to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "trust",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in them, and so would fail to enter into the kingdom of God, which requires absolute humility, ungrudging liberality, and constant self-denial.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
